<HEADLINE>
<P>
GOLF ROUNDUP; COUPLES' ONE-TWO PUNCH WINS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Fred Couples, recovering from a back injury that kept him out of golf for 
almost four months, shot a seven-under 65 Sunday morning, then had a 68 in the 
afternoon and beat Corey Pavin by two strokes in the Buick Open at Grand Blanc, 
Mich. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's very exciting. It was highly emotional for me," said Couples, who lost 
to Pavin by two strokes at the Los Angeles Open in February. "I had a lot of 
thoughts going through my mind." 
</P>
<P>
 Couples closed out his first victory of the season -- and the 11th of his 
career -- with a birdie on the final hole, hitting his seven-iron approach less 
than two feet from the pin and making the putt for a 270 total. 
</P>
<P>
 "Corey birdied 17. That kind of puts a lump in your throat," said Couples, who 
earned $198,000 of the $1.1-million purse. "But then I put it close and I was 
very, very happy. I knew this was a wonderful opportunity and I didn't want to 
waste it." 
</P>
<P>
 The 36-hole finish was necessary after the opening round was postponed 
Thursday because of rain. 
</P>
<P>
 Curtis Strange, Steve Pate and Greg Kraft were tied for third at 276. Ben 
Crenshaw and Keith Clearwater finished at 277. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Carolyn Hill shot a three-under 69 to win the McCall's LPGA Classic at 
Stratton Mountain, Vt., by three strokes over Nancy Ramsbottom. It was Hill's 
first victory in 14 years on the LPGA Tour. 
</P>
<P>
 Hill tied the tournament record with a 275 total. Ramsbottom, seeking her 
first victory in 10 years on the tour, shot a 70 for a 278. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Jim Albus saw his lead shrink to one stroke when he bogeyed the 15th hole, 
then birdied the next two holes to win the $700,000 Bank of Boston Senior PGA 
Classic at Concord, Mass., by two strokes. 
</P>
<P>
 Albus scored his second victory of the year with a two-under 70 that gave him 
a 54-hole total of 203, 13 under at the Nashawtuc Country Club. 
</P>
<P>
 Bob Brue, with a 65, and Raymond Floyd, with a 69, finished second with 205 
totals. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Tiger Woods of Cypress birdied the second hole and never trailed as he 
defeated Chris Riley, 2 and 1, to win the match-play championship at the 92nd 
Western Amateur tournament at Point O'Woods Golf and Country Club in Benton 
Harbor, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
 Woods, 18, moved to a 3-up lead with back-to-back birdies on the 10th and 11th 
holes. Riley, 20, of San Diego, birdied the 14th hole to cut Woods' lead to 2 
up, but Woods halved the next three holes. 
</P>
<P>
 "This win means a lot to me," Woods said. "All the big tournaments I've won 
until now have been junior tournaments. This is a great tournament on a great 
golf course. It really is the Masters of amateur golf." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Mark McNulty of Zimbabwe shot a course-record seven-under 65 to defeat Spain's 
Seve Ballesteros by a stroke and win the BMW International Open at Munich. 
</P>
</TEXT>
